32
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:44,500
And so we try to unravel from the

33
00:01:44,500 --> 00:01:48,000
scattering data what was going on inside the collision.

34
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:50,000
And inside the collision, of course, means

35
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:52,000
the properties of particles and so forth.

36
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:57,000
So the natural tool of experiment,

37
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:00,000
the scattering, and the natural thing

38
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:03,000
that a theorist would ask is,

39
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:06,000
if I have a theory of particles,

40
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:09,000
how do you compute the scattering amplitudes?

41
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:12,000
The scattering amplitudes, what is a scattering amplitude?

42
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:15,000
A scattering amplitude, you have some incoming

43
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:18,000
particles that are part of your incoming information.

44
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:21,000
I'm going to have time running this way tonight.

45
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:23,000
Horizontally instead of vertically.

46
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:25,000
I don't know why. Variety.

47
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:29,000
Particles come in, something happens inside

48
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:33,000
a black box, and particles go out.

49
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:37,000
Not necessarily the same number of particles.

50
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:40,000
The particles come in and they carry momentum.

51
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:42,000
Of course, they carry other things.

52
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:44,000
They carry spin, they carry charge,

53
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:47,500
they carry labels, like for example, is it a

54
00:02:47,500 --> 00:02:51,000
muon or is it a whatever it happens to be.

55
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:55,000
But let's simplify the story and ignore everything else.

56
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:58,000
They carry everything except their momentum.

57
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:02,000
So particles come in and they carry four momentum.

58
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:06,000
Four momentum means energy and momentum.

59
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:08,000
Let's write down what a four

60
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:10,000
vector of energy and momentum is.

61
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:16,000
The energy and the three components of momentum.

62
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:18,500
Of course, if we're working in

63
00:03:18,500 --> 00:03:21,000
26 dimensions, we have 25 components here.

64
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:23,000
But I'll just write down four of them.

65
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:26,000
So we have a four vector, relativistic four vector.

66
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:28,000
Each particle has a momentum.

67
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:32,000
And we're going to call it K.

68
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:34,000
K mu.

69
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:37,000
Where mu goes from one to four.

70
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:39,000
From zero to four, excuse me.

71
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:41,000
From zero to three. This is usually

72
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:43,000
called zero, one, two, three, doesn't matter.

73
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:46,000
Four components of momentum.

74
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:49,000
Now, what do we know about

75
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:52,000
the components, the four components of momentum

76
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:54,000
in a particle?

77
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:55,000
They have something to do

78
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:56,000
with the mass of the particle.

79
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:59,000
Well, of course, they are the energy and the momentum.

80
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:01,000
What's the relationship between energy and

81
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:03,000
momentum and mass for a relativistic particle?

82
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:05,000
Anybody remember? C is one.

83
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:10,000
We will take C equals H bar equals one.

84
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:13,000
What's the connection between the

85
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:16,000
components of energy, momentum, and mass?

86
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:19,000
E squared.

87
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:21,000
E squared.

88
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:26,000
E squared equals P squared plus M squared.

89
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Or, let's write it the following way.

90
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:36,000
E squared minus P squared equals M squared.

91
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:41,500
And just in order to keep my notation

92
00:04:41,500 --> 00:04:47,000
consistent with notations of physicists for many, many years,

93
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:50,000
I am going to write this as P squared

94
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:55,000
minus E squared equals minus M squared.

95
00:04:55,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Same formula, I've just taken the negative of it.

96
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:03,000
Now, that can also be written

97
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:06,000
in terms of the components of K.

98
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:07,500
In terms of the components

99
00:05:07,500 --> 00:05:09,000
of K, that's, what is it?

100
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:13,000
It's K naught squared, sorry, it's

101
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:17,000
K vector squared minus K naught squared.

102
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:20,000
Nought standing for the time component, E.

103
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:22,000
The spatial component squared

104
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:24,000
minus the time component squared.

105
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:27,000
And this is often just called K squared.

106
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:29,000
Just call it K squared.

107
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:34,000
The left-hand side here is the square by definition.

108
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:38,000
It's the definition of the relativistic square of a vector.

109
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:42,000
It's called P mu P mu.

110
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:48,000
Or, to simplify it, let's just call it K squared.

111
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:50,000
It's the space component squared

112
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:52,000
minus the time component squared.

113
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:54,000
That's called K squared.

114
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:57,500
And for every particle, K squared

115
00:05:57,500 --> 00:06:01,000
is equal to minus M squared.

116
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:04,000
You can't vary K squared.

117
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:06,000
Of course, K squared consists

118
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:08,000
of the energy and the momentum.

119
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:10,000
When you say you can't vary K squared,

120
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:12,000
it doesn't mean you can't vary the momentum.

121
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:14,000
It means when you vary the momentum,

122
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:16,000
the energy varies in a certain way.

123
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:18,000
And the way that it varies

124
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:20,000
is that E squared minus P squared,

125
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:22,500
or K times K naught squared minus

126
00:06:22,500 --> 00:06:25,000
K space squared, equals minus M squared.

127
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:32,000
So that's the first thing about...

128
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:35,000
It's not even about collisions. It's just about particles.

129
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:38,000
You characterize them by their four momentum,

130
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:41,000
three components of which are independent.

131
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:45,000
The fourth component has to be subject to this constraint.

132
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:48,000
And then a bunch of momentum.

133
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:52,000
Let's call this K1 for the first particle.

134
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:54,000
Is that the way I label them?

135
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:56,000
I like to keep my notation straight.

136
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Yeah. I think I call this one K1.

137
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:02,000
This one K2.

138
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:05,000
And then outgoing over here,

139
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:08,000
we'll call the incoming momentum K.

140
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:12,000
I'm going to call the outgoing momentum Q.

141
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:14,000
These are also four momenta.

142
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:16,000
I'm going to call it Q3.

143
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:18,000
Q4, dot dot dot.

144
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:20,000
Let's take the very simple case

145
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:23,000
in which two particles go to two particles.

146
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:27,000
Q4.

147
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:31,000
These particles come in.

148
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:33,000
Those particles go out.

149
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:36,000
How do you represent momentum conservation?

150
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:38,000
Momentum and energy conservation.

151
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:41,000
Momentum and energy conservation are simply

152
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:45,000
that K1 plus K2, thought of as four vectors,

153
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:48,000
equal to Q3 plus Q4.

154
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:53,000
All components.

155
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:56,000
The space components define momentum conservation.

156
00:07:56,000 --> 00:07:59,000
The time components define energy conservation.

157
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:01,000
Okay.

158
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:04,000
Now, because of the perversity of physicists,

159
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:06,000
what physicists like to do

160
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:10,000
is to redefine the outgoing momentum

161
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:13,000
and think of them as incoming momentum.

162
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:15,000
Now, that's crazy.

163
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:17,000
The incoming momentum and outgoing momentum are outgoing.

164
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:19,000
The incoming momentum and incoming momentum are incoming.

165
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:21,000
But to do it, all we really have to do

166
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:23,000
to make it symmetric

167
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:26,000
with respect to incoming and outgoing momentum,

168
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:28,000
just take each Q,

169
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Q4,

170
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:32,000
change its sign

171
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:37,000
and call it K.

172
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:41,000
Minus K3.

173
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:43,000
That means changing the sign of its energy.

174
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:45,000
It means changing the sign of all of its momentum.

175
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:48,500
It's a trick to be able

176
00:08:48,500 --> 00:08:52,000
to write this in a symmetric form.

177
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:54,000
Instead of writing K1, well, let's see what it is.

178
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:58,000
Here's what it is.

179
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:03,000
K1 plus K2 minus Q4 minus Q3 equals zero.

180
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:07,500
Now becomes K1 plus K2

181
00:09:07,500 --> 00:09:12,000
plus K3 plus K4 equals zero.

182
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:15,000
You treat all particles as incoming,

183
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:17,000
but you have to remember

184
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:20,000
that the label for the outgoing particles

185
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:22,000
is labeled with minus the

186
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:24,000
actual momentum of the outgoing particle,

187
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:26,000
but once you do so,

188
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:29,000
momentum conservation is completely symmetric

189
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:32,000
between the four particles.

190
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:34,000
A useful trick.

191
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:39,000
It's a useful trick that keeps labeling

192
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:41,000
especially consistent.

193
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:45,000
Notice that when you change the sign of the momentum

194
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:47,000
to redefine the momentum with a minus sign,

195
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:49,000
it does not change the fact

196
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:51,000
that the square of the momentum

197
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:53,000
is equal to minus M squared.

198
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:55,000
So we have in this particular process,

199
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:57,000
we have four momenta.

200
00:09:57,000 --> 00:09:59,000
Think of them as all incoming,

201
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:03,000
although the energies of two of them may be negative,

202
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:05,000
the outgoing ones.

203
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:08,000
Each one of them subject to this constraint.

204
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:11,000
The,

205
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:17,000
the question that a physicist would ask about this collision

206
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:19,000
is what is the amplitude?

207
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:21,000
What is the probability?

208
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:23,000
The thing, the amplitude is the thing that you square,

209
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:25,000
the complex number that you square

210
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:28,000
to find the probability for that collision.

211
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:30,000
But the collision is a function

212
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:33,000
of a number of variables.

213
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:36,000
It's a function, or the probability for the collision

214
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:40,000
is a function of the momenta of the incoming particles

215
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:42,000
and a function of the momentum of the outgoing particles.

216
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:45,000
So it's a function of the k's.

217
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:48,000
Let's call that amplitude A.

218
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:50,000
It's the thing that you square.

219
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:53,000
And it's a function of all of the k's,

220
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:56,000
k1, k2, k3, k4.

221
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:02,000
But there's some redundant information here.

222
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:05,000
First of all, the momenta have to be conserved.

223
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:07,000
Second of all, the square of

224
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:09,000
each k has to add up to,

225
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:11,000
to minus the mass squared.

226
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:13,000
So there's really too many variables here.

227
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:14,000
There's too many independent variables.

228
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:16,000
How many independent variables are there?

229
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:21,000
Before we impose any constraints,

230
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:23,000
each momentum has four variables.

231
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:26,500
This is 4 plus 4 is 8 plus

232
00:11:26,500 --> 00:11:30,000
4 is 12 plus 4 more is 16.

233
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:32,000
Okay, that's a lot of

234
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:34,000
variables for something to depend on.

235
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:38,000
Fortunately, you really don't depend on that many variables.

236
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:40,000
Let's think about, physically,

237
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:44,000
how many variables does a scattering amplitude

238
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:47,000
or a scattering process depend on?

239
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:49,000
Well, the first thing you can do is,

240
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:52,000
whatever the momenta are,

241
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:55,000
you can use relativity to

242
00:11:55,000 --> 00:11:58,000
go to a frame of reference

243
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:03,000
where the center of mass is at rest.

244
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:06,000
In other words, where the two momenta,

245
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:08,000
the two space components of the momentum,

246
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:10,000
are equal and opposite.

247
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:12,000
You can always do that.

248
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:16,000
If the particles are both moving down the z-axis,

249
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:17,500
well, you just move fast enough

250
00:12:17,500 --> 00:12:19,000
to be halfway in between them.

251
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:20,500
If they also happen to

252
00:12:20,500 --> 00:12:22,000
be moving in some other direction,

253
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:24,000
just move in that direction.

254
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:26,000
You can always go to a frame of reference

255
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:29,000
where the particles are equal and opposite,

256
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:32,000
the space components,

257
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:34,000
in other words, the spatial momenta.

258
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:38,000
Next, you can always rotate the momentum,

259
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:41,000
you can always rotate the system,

260
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:44,000
so that the momenta are coming in along the x-axis.

261
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:50,000
What's left over in the initial state,

262
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:53,500
what does it depend on if you

263
00:12:53,500 --> 00:12:57,000
know that the momenta are equal and opposite?

264
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:00,000
What does the whole thing depend on?

265
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:03,000
It only depends, what does the initial state depend on?

266
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:05,000
The initial state only depends

267
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:07,000
on the magnitude of the momentum.

268
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:10,000
Not the magnitude of the square of the momentum,

269
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:14,000
I mean, sorry, not the magnitude of the four vector.

270
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:17,000
The four vector has to have magnitude m squared,

271
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:20,000
but the magnitude of the space momentum.

272
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:22,000
Or the energy, if you like.

273
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:24,000
